commit 8386ad3c2a7bbb6ac03df7ae0e74ebbf888ef58a
Author: jrfnl <jrfnl@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Sat Feb 3 18:04:21 2018 +0100

    MultipleStatementAlignment: do not break on comments within arrays.
    
    Multi-line arrays interspersed with comments were treated differently than multi-line arrays without comments.
    
    This aligns the behaviour of both to be the same.
    
    Includes unit tests.

commit ec00a562bf190ef6986805fa6139a049de836bdd
Author: jrfnl <jrfnl@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Mon Oct 16 13:32:29 2017 +0200

    Squiz/MemberVarSpacing: add unit tests with trait import
    
    When traits are being imported, this is generally speaking the first statement in a class.
    
    This is not taken into account when determining whether a property is the first property in a class or not.
    
    Not fixed, but unit tests have been added to document the behaviour.

commit 2abe49c16c3cefb7e094836e20693eb3d6cad729
Author: jrfnl <jrfnl@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Mon Oct 16 13:30:25 2017 +0200

    Squiz/MemberVarSpacing: improve handling of multi-line multi-property declarations
    
    The sniff did not handle multi-property declarations well.
    Up to now, it would:
    * correct the number of lines above the line for each variable
    * not correct the number of lines above the line containing the scope keyword
    
    IMHO this is incorrect and only the lines above the line containing the scope keyword should be checked & fixed.
    
    This has now been fixed.
    
    By returning the `$stackPtr` of the semi-colon at the end of the property declaration, we skip past the additional variables.
    
    Includes unit tests.

commit e8b384eae8e9396451ce299ae59eed45453ba23f
Author: jrfnl <jrfnl@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Mon Oct 16 13:07:59 2017 +0200

    Abstract sniffs: allow to return a stackPtr to skip forward
    
    A "normal" sniff can return a `$stackPtr` to stop listening until the returned stack pointer is reached.
    
    This was, until now, not possible with the `AbstractScopeSniff` and by extension, the `AbstractVariableSniff`.

