commit 4989764ac7d631a868c0956149238e06ad253de8
Author: Kristof Coomans <kristof@statik.be>
Date:   Wed Jul 11 14:14:33 2012 +0200

    Use relative file path when matching with ignore patterns
    
    Currently the full, absolute path of a file is matched with the ignore
    patterns, which makes it difficult to specify patterns to ignore
    specific directories in a reusable way.
    
    For example when running phpcs on a Drupal-based project located at
    "/home/cyberwolf/myproject/", you'd like to ignore the "includes"
    directory in the root of your project, because it contains Drupal core
    code. However, other non-core directories can contain a directory
    called "includes" as well, which you do not want to ignore while
    scanning, for example
    "/home/cyberwolf/myproject/sites/all/modules/foo/includes". Currently,
    to accomplish this, an ignore pattern with the absolute path needs to
    be specified, for example "/home/cyberwolf/myproject/includes". This is
    not reusable on other systems where the project might be checked out at
    another path. Specifying "includes" would lead to phpcs also ignoring
    "/home/cyberwolf/myproject/sites/all/modules/foo/includes".
    
    This patch makes the file path being matched with the ignore patterns
    relative to the directory specified for scanning, so "includes" will be
    used for matching instead of "/home/cyberwolf/myproject/includes",
    "sites/all/modules/foo/includes" will be used for matching instead of
    "home/cyberwolf/myproject/sites/all/modules/foo/includes", and so on.
    Using "^includes" as an ignore pattern now will succesfully ignore
    everything in the "/home/cyberwolf/myproject/includes" dir and nothing
    else.

commit 21371b3241b6d084920e59c198c4e9d75c544dd0
Author: Greg Sherwood <gsherwood@squiz.net>
